1 5–212.
2 (a) The target per pupil foundation amount includes costs associated with
3 implementing the Blueprint for Maryland’s Future including:
4 (1) Increasing salaries;
5 (2) Additional teachers to provide professional learning and collaborative
6 time for teachers;
7 (3) Career counseling;
8 (4) Behavioral health;
9 (5) Instructional opportunities for students who are college and career
10 ready and those who are not;
11 (6) Maintenance and operation of schools;
12 (7) Supplies and materials for teachers; and
13 (8) Educational technology including digital devices, broadband
14 connectivity, [and] information technology staff, AND CYBERSECURITY.
15 (b) Schools may use funds provided under this section to provide the programs
16 required under COMAR 13A.04.16.01.
17 (c) (1) [County boards of education and schools shall prioritize the purchase
18 of digital devices for using funds under subsection (a)(8) of this section.
19 (2)] Additional funds provided in the target per pupil foundation amount for
20 educational technology are intended to supplement and not supplant existing funding
21 provided for educational technology.
22 [(3)] (2) (i) On or before [November 15 each year] AUGUST 15, 2026,
23 AND EACH AUGUST 15 THEREAFTER, each county board shall submit a report to the
24 Department detailing, for the previous fiscal year:
25 1. The amount spent by the local school system on technology
26 disaggregated by digital devices, connectivity, and information technology staff; [and]
27 2. The percentage of students, teachers, and staff with
28 digital devices and adequate connectivity in their homes in accordance with the Federal
29 Communications Commission standards for broadband; AND

4 HOUSE BILL 957
1 3. CYBERSECURITY EXPENDITURES RELATED TO THE
2 STATE MINIMUM CYBERSECURITY STANDARDS ESTABLISHED BY THE DEPARTMENT
3 OF INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY.
4 (ii) On or before December 15 each year, the Department shall
5 submit to the General Assembly, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government
6 Article, a compilation of the reports submitted to the Department under subparagraph (i)
7 of this paragraph.
8 (iii) On or before September 1, 2021, the Department shall establish
9 uniform reporting requirements, including definitions to ensure that consistent and
10 comparable reports are submitted under subparagraph (i) of this paragraph.
11 Article – State Finance and Procurement
12 3.5–101.
13 (a) In this title the following words have the meanings indicated.
14 (b) “Cloud computing” means a service that enables on–demand self–service
15 network access to a shared pool of configurable computer resources, including data storage,
16 analytics, commerce, streaming, e–mail, document sharing, and document editing.
17 (c) “Department” means the Department of Information Technology.
18 (d) (1) “Oversight of implementation” means management of the process to
19 implement a new technology, system, or product into practice and use by a unit.
20 (2) “Oversight of implementation” includes:
21 (i) planning and preparation to implement the product or practice;
22 and
23 (ii) ongoing monitoring and support of the implementation team to
24 ensure successful execution and that the project goals are met.
25 (3) “Oversight of implementation” does not include:
26 (i) responsibility for day–to–day management of any individual
27 projects or products; or
28 (ii) responsibility for implementing individual–level process
29 requirements for a project or product.
30 (e) “Secretary” means the Secretary of Information Technology.

HOUSE BILL 957 5
1 (F) “STATE MINIMUM CYBERSECURITY STANDARDS” MEANS THE STATE
2 MINIMUM CYBERSECURITY STANDARDS ESTABLISHED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF
3 INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY.
4 [(f)] (G) “Telecommunication” means the transmission of information, images,
5 pictures, voice, or data by radio, video, or other electronic or impulse means.
6 [(g)] (H) “Unit of State government” means an agency or unit of the Executive
7 Branch of State government.
8 3.5–2A–02.
9 There is an Office of Security Management within the Department.
10 3.5–2A–04.
11 (b) The Office shall:
12 (1) establish standards to categorize all information collected or
13 maintained by or on behalf of each unit of State government;
14 (2) establish standards to categorize all information systems maintained
15 by or on behalf of each unit of State government;
16 (3) develop guidelines governing the types of information and information
17 systems to be included in each category;
18 (4) establish security requirements for information and information
19 systems in each category;
20 (5) assess the categorization of information and information systems and
21 the associated implementation of the security requirements established under item (4) of
22 this subsection;
23 (6) if the State Chief Information Security Officer determines that there
24 are security vulnerabilities or deficiencies in any information systems, determine and direct
25 or take actions necessary to correct or remediate the vulnerabilities or deficiencies, which
26 may include requiring the information system to be disconnected;
27 (7) if the State Chief Information Security Officer determines that there is
28 a cybersecurity threat caused by, affecting, or potentially affecting an entity connected to
29 the network established under § 3.5–404 of this title that introduces or may introduce a
30 serious risk to entities connected to the network or to the State, take or direct actions
31 required to mitigate the threat;
32 (8) manage security awareness training for all appropriate employees of
33 units of State government;

6 HOUSE BILL 957
1 (9) assist in the development of data management, data governance, and
2 data specification standards to promote standardization and reduce risk;
3 (10) assist in the development of a digital identity standard and
4 specification applicable to all parties communicating, interacting, or conducting business
5 with or on behalf of a unit of State government;
6 (11) develop and maintain information technology security policy,
7 standards, and guidance documents, consistent with best practices developed by the
8 National Institute of Standards and Technology;
9 (12) to the extent practicable, seek, identify, and inform relevant
10 stakeholders of any available financial assistance provided by the federal government or
11 non–State entities to support the work of the Office;
12 (13) provide technical assistance to localities in mitigating and recovering
13 from cybersecurity incidents;
14 (14) ANNUALLY REVIEW AND, IF NECESSARY, UPDATE THE STATE
15 MINIMUM CYBERSECURITY STANDARDS;
16 [(14)] (15) provide technical services, advice, and guidance to units of local
17 government to improve cybersecurity preparedness, prevention, response, and recovery
18 practices; and
19 [(15)] (16) support local governments in developing a vulnerability
20 assessment and cyber assessment, including providing local governments with the
21 resources and information on best practices to complete the assessments.
22 3.5–406.
23 (a) This section does not apply to municipal governments.
24 (b) In a manner and frequency established in regulations adopted by the
25 Department, each county government, local school system, and local health department
26 shall:
27 (1) in consultation with the local emergency manager, create or update a
28 cybersecurity preparedness and response plan; and
29 (2) complete a cybersecurity preparedness assessment.
30 (c) The assessment required under paragraph (b)(2) of this section may, in
31 accordance with the preference of each county government, be performed by the
32 Department or by a vendor authorized by the Department.

HOUSE BILL 957 7
1 (D) (1) THE DEPARTMENT’S INFORMATION SECURITY OFFICERS ON
2 REQUEST, THE DEPARTMENT SHALL SUPPORT ADVISE LOCAL SCHOOL SYSTEMS
3 WITH ON:
4 (1) (I) COMPLIANCE WITH THE STATE MINIMUM CYBERSECURITY
5 STANDARDS;
6 (2) (II) CONDUCTING CYBERSECURITY MATURITY ASSESSMENTS
7 EVERY 2 YEARS; AND
8 (3) (III) REMEDIATION EFFORTS.
9 (2) THE DEPARTMENT IS NOT RESPONSIBLE FOR THE SUCCESSFUL
10 PERFORMANCE OF OR DAY–TO–DAY MANAGEMENT OF THE DUTIES OF A LOCAL
11 SCHOOL SYSTEM DESCRIBED IN PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS SUBSECTION.
12 [(d)] (E) (1) Each local government shall report a cybersecurity incident,
13 including an attack on a State system being used by the local government, to the
14 appropriate local emergency manager and the State Security Operations Center in the
15 Department in accordance with paragraph (2) of this subsection.
16 (2) For the reporting of cybersecurity incidents to local emergency
17 managers under [subparagraph (i) of this paragraph] PARAGRAPH (1) OF THIS
18 SUBSECTION, the State Chief Information Security Officer shall determine:
19 (i) the criteria for determining when an incident must be reported;
20 (ii) the manner in which to report; and
21 (iii) the time period within which a report must be made.
22 (3) The State Security Operations Center shall immediately notify the
23 appropriate agencies of a cybersecurity incident reported under this subsection through the
24 State Security Operations Center.
25 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That, for the 2026–2027 school
26 year, the Department of Information Technology shall focus on Standard 6.2 Protect (PR)
27 Controls of the State minimum cybersecurity standards.
28 SECTION 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
29 1, 2026.

